## Key Context for Families

**Three-Tier Structure:** These are not three separate programs competing for the same people — they're a tiered system. If someone's income is too high for QMB, they may qualify for SLMB. If too high for SLMB, they may qualify for QI. Each tier covers progressively less but serves people with higher incomes.[1][3][4]

**Income Limits Are Tied to Poverty Level:** The dollar amounts shown above are for 2026 and will change in April 2027 when the federal poverty level is announced. Families should expect these numbers to shift annually.[1]

**QI Funding Crisis:** The QI program is the most precarious. It receives a fixed annual budget from the federal government. Once that money is spent, the program stops accepting new applicants for that calendar year — even if someone is otherwise eligible. This can happen mid-year. Eligibility is not guaranteed to continue into the next year.[3]

**Processing Timelines Vary:** QMB applications should be processed within 45 days, but SLMB and QI applications can be made retroactive up to 3 months, meaning a family could receive back payments if approved.[1]

**What Counts as "Income" Matters:** The program excludes certain income when calculating eligibility (first $20 of any income, first $65 of wages, half of wages above that). This can push someone just over the limit into eligibility.[5]

**Asset Limits Are Real:** Families cannot have more than $9,950 in countable assets (individual) or $14,910 (couple). However, the primary home, one vehicle, and certain other items don't count. Savings accounts and investments do count.[4][6]

To apply, contact the **Utah Department of Health and Human Services Medicaid office** directly for current phone numbers, online application portals, and specific forms required, as these details were not available in the search results provided.[3]

